				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Auburn, Wash. – Sixteen Charles Wright Academy Upper Schoolers are moving on to the Washington state National History Day competition in May after placing in the top three in their respective categories at the South Puget Sound regional competition at Green River Community College on Thursday, March 26. It is the largest group of Tarriers to advance to state since CWA started participating in the program. </p>
<p>Twenty-four students competed in seven categories at the regional level—individual documentary, paper, individual exhibit, individual website, group performance, individual performance, and group website. A Tarrier placed first in five out of those seven categories:</p>
<p>Sean O&#8217;Farrell &#8217;17 for his project &#8220;Bruce Crandell—The Leader of Modern Helicopter Aviation&#8221; (individual documentary)</p>
<p>Miranda Ferguson &#8217;16 for her project &#8220;Creation of an Empire: The Leadership and Legacy of Queen Anne I&#8221; (paper)</p>
<p>Kaylee Kim &#8217;16 for her project &#8220;Nico Roozen: The Founder of Fair Trade&#8221; (individual exhibit)</p>
<p>Angel Ortiz &#8217;18 for his project &#8220;Judge Julius W. Waring&#8221; (individual website)</p>
<p>Drew Snyder &#8217;18, Jackie Yeh &#8217;16, Morgan Potter &#8217;16, and Wyatt Swift &#8217;17 for their project &#8220;Raphael Lemkin&#8221; (group performance—pictured above)</p>
<p>All students who place at the regional level move on to the state competition, which will be held May 2, also at Green River Community College. The national competition takes place in mid-June at the University of Maryland in College Park. See below for the full list of Tarrier participation at the regional level, and best of luck to those students moving on!</p>
<p>Individual Documentary<br />
1st place: Sean O&#8217;Farrell &#8217;17 for &#8220;Bruce Crandell—The Leader of Modern Helicopter Aviation&#8221;<br />
2nd place: Piper Coyner &#8217;18 for &#8220;The Leadership and Legacy of Hap Arnold&#8221;<br />
3rd place: Hayden Saafeld &#8217;18 for &#8220;Chief Leschi&#8221;</p>
<p>Ashley Nelson &#8217;18 with &#8220;Christiaan Barnard&#8221;</p>
<p>Paper<br />
1st place: Miranda Ferguson &#8217;16 for &#8220;Creation of an Empire: The Leadership and Legacy of Queen Anne I&#8221;<br />
3rd place: Noah Fields &#8217;18 for &#8220;Thurgood Marshall&#8221;</p>
<p>Sienna Kuehnis &#8217;17 with &#8220;Nelson Vails—Riding Through History&#8221;<br />
Nathan Samanmit &#8217;17 with &#8220;General Patton—America&#8217;s Greatest Military Leader&#8221;</p>
<p>Individual Exhibit<br />
1st place: Kaylee Kim &#8217;16 for &#8220;Nico Roozen: The Founder of Fair Trade&#8221;<br />
3rd place: Alli Knowles &#8217;17 for &#8220;Sally Ride&#8221;</p>
<p>Alexis Schorno &#8217;17 with &#8220;Paul Farmer—Leading Medicine into the 21st Century&#8221;</p>
<p>Individual Website<br />
1st place: Angel Ortiz &#8217;18 for &#8220;Judge Julius W. Waring&#8221;<br />
3rd place: Kashava Katti for &#8220;John Locke&#8221;</p>
<p>Mei Ge &#8217;18 with &#8220;Bobby Sands—A Legacy of Leadership&#8221;<br />
Jonathan Zacarias &#8217;18 with &#8220;Sergei Korolev&#8221;</p>
<p>Group Performance<br />
1st place: Drew Snyder &#8217;18, Jackie Yeh &#8217;16, Morgan Potter&#8217;16, and Wyatt Swift &#8217;17 for &#8220;Raphael Lemkin&#8221;</p>
<p>Individual Performance<br />
3rd place: Abby Webster &#8217;18 for &#8220;The Leadership and Legacy of Eleanor Creasy&#8221;</p>
<p>Emily Halladay &#8217;18 with &#8220;Preparation for a New Age in AIDS Research&#8221;</p>
<p>Group Website<br />
2nd place: Youmna Hassan &#8217;17 and Ann Thompson &#8217;18 for &#8220;Eleanor Roosevelt&#8221;</p>
